Creating a single constructor with flags to specify rendering options can work well and make your API cleaner, especially if you don't want to expose all the details of the SDL_ttf library but still want to offer flexibility.

Here's an example of how you might structure such a constructor:

```cpp
enum class TextQuality {
    Solid,    // Fastest, no anti-aliasing, suitable for high performance
    Shaded,   // Anti-aliased with a background color, readable on any background
    Blended   // High quality, anti-aliased, and uses alpha blending
};

class Surface {
public:
    Surface(const std::string& text, Font& font, int fontSize, const Color& fgColor, const Color& bgColor = {0, 0, 0, 0}, TextQuality quality = TextQuality::Blended);
