// Implementation of the Surface constructor
Surface::Surface(const std::string& text, Font& font, int fontSize, const Color& fgColor, const Color& bgColor, TextQuality quality) {
    switch (quality) {
        case TextQuality::Solid:
            surface = TTF_RenderText_Solid(font.GetFont(fontSize), text.c_str(), { fgColor.R, fgColor.G, fgColor.B, fgColor.A });
            break;
        case TextQuality::Shaded:
            surface = TTF_RenderText_Shaded(font.GetFont(fontSize), text.c_str(), { fgColor.R, fgColor.G, fgColor.B, fgColor.A }, { bgColor.R, bgColor.G, bgColor.B, bgColor.A });
            break;
        case TextQuality::Blended:
            surface = TTF_RenderText_Blended(font.GetFont(fontSize), text.c_str(), { fgColor.R, fgColor.G, fgColor.B, fgColor.A });
            break;
        default:
            throw std::invalid_argument("Unknown text quality option");
    }

    if (surface == nullptr) {
        std::string errorMsg = "ERROR: Surface for font '" + font.GetFontPath() + "' could not be created: " + SDL_GetError();
        SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, errorMsg.c_str());
        throw std::runtime_error(errorMsg);
    }
}
```

The `TextQuality` enum contains options that reflect the three rendering methods you mentioned. Users of your `Surface` class can then choose the desired quality when creating a text surface. By providing a default for `quality`, you allow users to omit this parameter if they're happy with the default, which would be `TextQuality::Blended` in this case. The same goes for the `bgColor` in case they use the `TextQuality::Shaded` quality; they can omit it if they don't want to specify a background color.

This approach encapsulates the decision-making about which SDL_ttf function to use within the `Surface` class and provides an easy way to adjust text rendering quality without getting into the specifics of each SDL_ttf rendering method. This may be an ideal approach if your intent is to offer a simple API while still retaining the flexibility to adjust for performance or appearance as needed.

Using bool variables instead of an enum class can work for a simpler API with fewer rendering options. However, using bools can quickly become limiting and confusing if more than two rendering styles are involved. For instance, if you have just a flag for anti-aliasing, it's not clear how it would differentiate between `Shaded` and `Blended` rendering, which both involve anti-aliasing.

If you are certain you want to offer a very simplified API with only two rendering styles—let's say, for example, `Solid` and `Blended`—you could use a bool flag to switch between them. Here is an example:

```cpp
class Surface {
public:
    // Constructor with anti-aliasing flag
    Surface(const std::string& text, Font& font, int fontSize, const Color& color, bool antiAliased = true);

    // ... other members and methods ...
};

// Implementation of the Surface constructor with anti-aliasing flag
Surface::Surface(const std::string& text, Font& font, int fontSize, const Color& color, bool antiAliased) {
    if (antiAliased) {
        // Use blended (anti-aliased) rendering
        surface = TTF_RenderText_Blended(font.GetFont(fontSize), text.c_str(), { color.R, color.G, color.B, color.A });
    } else {
        // Use solid (no anti-aliasing) rendering
        surface = TTF_RenderText_Solid(font.GetFont(fontSize), text.c_str(), { color.R, color.G, color.B, color.A });
    }

    if (surface == nullptr) {
        std::string errorMsg = "ERROR: Surface for font '" + font.GetFontPath() + "' could not be created: " + SDL_GetError();
        SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, errorMsg.c_str());
        throw std::runtime_error(errorMsg);
    }
}
```

In this code, `antiAliased` is a flag that determines whether `TTF_RenderText_Blended` (anti-aliased) or `TTF_RenderText_Solid` (non-anti-aliased) is used for rendering. This approach is quite limited and lacks future extensibility. If you have plans to support more text rendering styles in the future, or want to differentiate between different types of anti-aliasing (such as `Shaded` vs. `Blended`), using an enum is more descriptive and scalable.

Here are some general guidelines:

1. If you **only ever** plan to offer two straightforward options (e.g., with or without anti-aliasing), then a bool flag might suffice.
2. If you envision offering more rendering styles or options, or if you want to provide the user with more descriptive choices, an enum class is likely more appropriate.
3. If you expect to add further quality or style options in the future, implementing an enum from the start will save you from redesigning the API later on.

In general, enums are preferred when there are multiple options that are mutually exclusive, as they help create a clearer and more maintainable API.

